div.p:
Catalysts of precious metal (Rh, Ru, Pt) have high performance in the DRM reaction (Tsyganok et al.


  2003


). Among them, Ru and Rh catalysts show high catalytic activity and good anti-coking properties. Precious metals have high oxygen affinity, which promotes the coke gasification on the catalyst surface (Zhou et al.


  2018


). However, precious metals are expensive (Ru: 27,258 $/kg) and thus incur high costs for large-scale commercial processes. Hence, relatively inexpensive Ni (18.87 $/kg) catalysts are used for commercial purposes. While the Ni catalyst is more liable to coke deposition and sintering compared with the precious metal catalysts, and the catalyst is easily deactivated despite its excellent catalytic activity (Rostrupnielsen and Hansen


  1993


).

These previous studies are mainly aimed at developing a durable catalyst that has excellent activity at low temperatures and high coking resistance. A small amount of a precious metal catalyst is added to Ni catalyst to prepare a bimetallic catalyst (Zhou et al.


  2018


). Generally, the precious metal improves the reducing property of Ni and lowers its reduction temperature (Tengfei et al.


  2015


). This is because H

 2

molecules are dissociated from the precious metal atoms owing to the H

 2

spillover effect, and the dissociated H atom is diffused throughout the non-precious metal catalyst surface (Lucci et al.


  2015


). Also, Ru has high durable on the DRM reaction, since, Ru promotes coke gasification due to high oxygen affinity (Jones et al.


  2008


).

Although many previous studies have been performed on Ni-Ru catalysts, their preparation and the order of active metal loading have not been extensively investigated. Since the preparation method and the order of the active metals (with equal loading amounts) influences the performance of the resulting catalyst, the optimization of such processes is an important factor in terms of catalyst development. Although the impregnation method is the most widely applied preparation method (Şener et al.


  2018


), unlike the deposition-precipitation method (Rodriguez-Gomez, Pereniguez, and Caballero


  2018


), it does not provide high metal dispersion. In this study, we developed an optimal preparation method for enhancing coke resistance. The catalytic performances achieved using the different preparation methods (impregnation or deposition-precipitation) and active metal loading procedure were compared, particularly for Ni catalysts and Ni-Ru bimetallic catalysts.

